I've had the pixel 5 now since November and I'm not a fan. The 765 snapdragon seems to be the reason for me. The system crashes constantly, it can't transition well at all after about an hour of use(meaning it becomes choppy from app to app), and got to experience the fun of the system not transitioning daylight savings time an almost missing work(which I found out happened only in the pixel 5). Now I'll be fair because I enjoyed this phone so much in the first 2 months, the fingerprint reader is amazing an simple, the camera offers great versatility, screen call is very useful, and it's probably the only phone I'm not afraid to drop, however the negatives really made me realize how cheap Google is. The 765 is shit, I'm tired of reviewers that use a phone for a week or a month trying to sell this as a positive, it isn't a good thing at all. Battery saver mode kills the abilities completely on this phone which makes it a useless mode, my apps crash or become choppy in it like crazy, and the speakers on this phone are horrible, they should of put an audio jack on the phone, but the goal is to be like apple, you can tell by Google's software setup. Now I'm going to stress this, I got this phone for 450 dollars brand new and I regret it. I was hoping for a simple phone that runs well and does the basics well and has a good to great camera. That's what Google markets it as, but it's only that for 2 months. Google does not make this phone to last. I'll be looking to another brand in the future, don't waste your money. If it was even 300 dollars I would talk you out of it because the phone won't last. An if people think I'm harsh, it's because there should be no excuse for this price with this low quality of hardware. Oh yeah I forgot the only other positive, the phone is so cheap, it's cheap to repair.

it's that time again, YouTube smartphone review time and I think it says a lot for you that for me, new smartphone time is synonymous with Marques Brownlee review time. It just wouldn't be the same without it! There was some other guy I really liked but I forget who he is now. One thing I've learned is phone reviewers really have this thing for bezels or lack of them but that's not for me. I had an HTC U11 before the Pixel 3 XL I use now which I loved, just its motherboard got fried and I liked the large bottom bezel for aesthetics. I thought it looked cool and I must say nearly full screens are annoying to me or at least because it's sometimes too easy to touch the screen and launch something you don't want to. The other thing about phone reviews is that the keyboard functionality and layout never gets discussed but it's a really important part of a phone to me as it's something you use a lot. For example, the location of special characters in the Pixel 3 keyboard is terrible and counter-intuitive to me. The percentage sign for example is located in the second special character screen and it's pretty annoying. You can only archive dodgy SMS threads as well, on all other smartphones I've used you can lock them away with a PIN. That being said, there are a lot of other great features and neat functionality on the Pixel 3XL I really like. The camera as you say is second to none except maybe the Xperia 1 ii which is the new phone I want and although I won't be getting a Pixel again, on another level I can't imagine living without a camera this good. I'd say the Pixel is really a very, very good phone you come to like a lot rather than love which I have all my other smartphones. Even an old Nokia Lumia windows phone from years ago which for its major UI & OS problems I still loved because the UI was otherwise really nice and it had some great other features. The HTC U11 did also have an excellent camera and again, I loved it whereas by comparison I just like the Pixel 3XL very much even though with its overall operation it deserves better than that. I say that the Pixel is the "Microsoft Lumia of today". It's a little plain, a bit nerdy but it's otherwise a very good phone. I was a little shocked watching your Galaxy S20 review, I didn't like the camera, it is as you said just a little too sharp. It certainly doesn't stack up even to the Pixel 3 XL's camera in my opinion. My phone has a few other irritating quirks but overall I still really like it, functions really well still after 20 months, and a lot of the Google/Pixel specific features and functionality work really, really well. It was praised in reviews for being "pure Android" and I can see why, that aspect of it is really good and makes for a very clean and uncluttered user experience. Which in some ways I can't imagine living without again but still, I've always wanted to try the Xperia, I love what I know about the Xperia 1 ii, it's going to be my next smartphone and because I want a phone I can love again, not merely like very much, I wouldn't get a Pixel again, for all that's good with it.

Google is hitting their mark. Around 2014, google set to make their software ultra efficient to supply inexpensive devices in 3rd world markets, like educational tablets on the cheap. Seems the core technology is trickling to current devices, where you can build new devices with older components but still making them incredibly competitive. This gives Google an edge on production cost. You basically can almost bundle cheap devices with services. AT&T, Verizon this week launch a $5 add on to your plan and get a 4a, Google launch a $15 monthly subscription and it comes with crack screen protection and a new phone replacement every two years. Their basically giving their phones away. If this business model of product distribution picks up steam, say good bye to many flagships as pressure will increase for them to become either less expensive or very innovative. Either way we all win.

I'm not sure if the SD765g supports 120hz displays. Hypothetically, the bandwidth is there as it supports a QHD+ resolution, which at a standard 60hz should give it roughly the same pixels resolved per second as a FHD+ at 120hz (depending on screen aspect ratio since QHD is only 2x as many pixels as FHD when both are the same aspect ratio). Qualcomm may have limited the 765g in this regard to help keep the SD865 and 865+ cemented with higher end features since 5g lost its exclusivity in their lineup when the newest 700 series chips were introduced).

Does the Pixel 5 really need a 120hz display? Maybe but the jump from 60hz to 90hz is a 50% increase while 90hz to 120hz is only a 33% increase. So the law of diminishing returns comes into play. If the Pixel managed a 865/120hz display, it wouldn't have been likely to compete directly with the likes of the OnePlus 8t and S20 FE in price. Once you leapfrog those devices, the competition would all be offering telephoto lenses (which the FE already does) so some shopping in the higher end $800-$1000 range may see this hypothetical permutation as inferior. The usefulness of telephoto lenses is kinda a question mark for me. On one hand, I see a lot of manufacturers starting to opt for higher quality secondary and tertiary lenses which give them the ability to hold up in quality (upping zoom levels to 3x helps this a lot too) vs the standard lens and sensor arrangement. On the other, I find a lot of budget minded to midrange devices going all out on multi camera arrays despite a lot of the extra sensors being lower quality. With regards to telephoto lenses in particular, this can make them a bit superfluous in many situations outside of optimal lighting conditions since the primary lens/sensor can often produce a better image cropped down than a 2x lens and a smaller, lower quality sensor can. This concept doesn't apply much to other camera types like macro or ultra wide sensors as they are simply capable of forms of imagery and filming that are impossible for a standard lens. Super short focal distance and extra wide FoV aren't possible with these, shout out to Motorola for the dope sounding, I've never used one video centric lens used for taking landscape with the device held in portrait (lol I realize I sound like a Marquez transcript with that last sentence).

As a total package, I'd call the Pixel 5 "highly competitive and focused towards its price point and intended demographic" as it is a very good all around package despite its few shortcomings (all cuts that I don't think most smartphone users will notice or care about) while putting its sights clearly on a segment of the industry and the typical smartphone user in both price and feature set to help cement it as an easy choice to recommend to people walking into a carrier/electronics store or shopping around without a definitive answer as to what they want.

Tech heads are usually the type to have their minds made up already when searching for a new smartphone. Sure, a hands on at a store might sway them but a lot of "average consumers" (Jud reference, thank you for getting me back onto his channel with you're guys' s20 collab that I peaked back to because I've been itching for an upgrade lol techtober is a tough month between new devices and discounted ones) aren't sure of what they want and don't know everything (or really that much most times) about even their primary choice walking into a store or shopping online.

The Pixel 5 is one of those phones that I can see a lot of these folks seeing and saying "I didn't even know Google made phones" and come away with one that day after a solid overall experience with the software/build, great price to feature ratio, and a bunch of Pixel exclusive features that are aimed at the masses between the exclusive assistant features and the highly streamlined, optimized yet varied and easy to use camera features.

I give props to Google for hitting all these points yet still making a device I, as a tech enthusiast, want and would use myself. This device is primed to be the best selling Pixel ever (though the 4a will likely give it great competition due to a similar level of hardware/price excellence). Getting a larger market share is key for Google in my opinion, since doing so will allow them to integrate unique hardware elements like the Pixel nueral core (which isn't all that useful anymore considering the focus on AI computation with this years snapdragon 700/800 lineup), the squeeze sensitive frame, and the Soli radar chip. Giving a phone hardware like this is cool on it's own but if they do so with a significant market share (and open up the APIs driving them like they did with Soli), 3rd party devs will be more likely to integrate them into their applications. Soli in particular seemed like it could've been a real game changer if the gestures had been widely adopted and if Covid19 hadn't ruined the primary authentication method for Pixel 4 users (I'm now wondering how much iPhone sales outside of the SE have suffered due to the pandemic and if Apple opted for TouchID for the iPad Air to help initial sales before the quarantine policies regarding masks are lifted).

The Pixel 5 is a step back to their roots, more affordable, cheaper components, missing features and a middle of the road price. That sounds great, the problem is when they did this before there was far less competition. Now we have mid-range phones that would beat out flagships of just a few years ago! So the Pixel 5 is now priced with the best in that sector but features that are priced closer to $400. In Europe the pricing is less, probably an acknowledgement to the competition from China, but it still means you are paying for that Google logo. In the US for political reasons competition is far less so they can get away with charging at the very high end of mid-rangers.

With other OEMs like OnePlus and Samsung now offering the same years of upgrades and with camera tech now closer than ever, two reasons to buy a pixel are mute. The downgrade of the speakers was one reason I bought one, so the Pixel 5 fails here. So why buy a Pixel anymore when you can get better for less? For me, there is no reason and I would not recommend it at the US or UK retail pricing.

Let's make something perfectly clear: you CAN NOT SEE ANYTHING FASTER THAN 30 Hz!!!!

The differences you are seeing has nothing whatsoever with the actual screen's physical refresh rate. What you are seeing is the graphics hardware's ability to properly and fully process the image data at a rate that keeps up with your eye's refresh rate, which is 30 hz, regardless of what you may think. The truth is that between the OS, the app, and the graphics hardware there are a lot of things going on that create inconsistencies and hiccups that you can detect, not because you have superhuman, "trained" eyes, but because they are obvious to everybody because every 30 Hz frame is not rendered perfectly, in perfect sync or without repeated frames. Even if 60 Hz or more is being reported by whatever utility you are using, there are not 60 perfectly clear, perfectly timed and perfectly spaced frames being rendered and pushed to the display by the hardware. In fact, there usually aren't even 30 frames being perfectly rendered in that time. There is a gigantic difference between being displayed and being perfectly displayed.

The point here is that anything above 60 Hz for the display itself is an absolute waste of money and resources. What makes a far bigger impact is the ability of the rendering engine to deliver frames perfectly and consistently. It's a very complicated issue that is affected just as much by how much the OS allows interruptions to processing and display and other factors. What's true is that with the faster displays is also included much more powerful computing and rendering hardware that can more readily overcome all the obstacles to consistent frame rendering. It's the behind the scenes hardware, not the display itself, that makes the difference.

That said, there is also the fact that the specs of displays are at best misleading and often outright lies. Of two displays that are rated the same, one might actually be capable of (nearly) perfectly reproducing frames at that rate, while another is still showing a ghost of the last frame while the current one is supposed to be showing clearly. But ironically, the lower-quality one with the ghosted image will actually appear smoother to the human eye.

Which is exactly why I hate 24 fps so much. 24 fps is definitely slower than the human eye, and I can't get past the flickering/strobing effect. Don't tell me 24 fps "cinema mode" is better. It's absolutely NOT*. It yanks me completely out of the suspension of disbelief and slaps me in the face with the fact that I'm *only watching a film. The same goes for grain. It may be artsy, but it definitely isn't good.

Maybe I'm cynical or actually tuned in to how these companies work, but I saw the same thing happen to OnePlus and this just smacks of the same kinda thing. OnePlus went through a bell curve though instead of a sharp decline like Google are going through.

What I'm talking about is OnePlus starting off as the budget flagship killer (it's what made me get the 5T), then they completely went back on what made them great from that point on. Only recently with the Nord they're remembering where they used to be. Bell curve.

Google seems to have failed in their expectations or are trying to reinvent themselves with the budget-mid range phones, but a part of me wonders if they're doing it as a cheap way to get people into the Pixel family so they can use that future loyalty to get away with pushing the high-end price ranges again. That's just business I suppose, but I'm a consumer not a Google CEO.

These companies want that fashion statement badge like Apple have. Look at the shit Apple have been pulling for years and still pull to this day with not including a charging brick. Started with the headphones. Constantly pushing the boat out and raising the price of a seat.

I'll get a 4a soon because it'll give me a good 3 or 4 years like my 5T has, but whether or not they'll keep me onboard after that is up to them. OnePlus certainly aren't keeping me onboard and that's after one product of theirs that I've owned.

I like your reviews, and I have been thinking about Dave Lee's Pixel take on "not competing with a flagship of their own". Something you mentioned here. And I (respectfully) disagree.

I can't shake the feeling that they ARE holding back. I bet there will be a 5a or a 5XL version coming next year that will make this one obsolete. Because the hardware simply doesn't justify the price. Other manufacturers like Samsung and Oneplus are competing with their flagships and STILL put better hardware on their midrangers.

What it looks like to me is that now that they have no flagships, Google was set to be a flagship killer. Something that is not high end, but is unquestionably better market value. And this isn't it. We had a good flagship killer in the form of Xiaomi for the last years, and now that they have a flagship, they are for sure holding back: their 10T was very underwhelming.

The market for flagship killers is up for grabs, Google could easily occupy this market by producing phones that are unquestionably better valued (they have the tech for it, and they make money just by pushing the software, something Xiaomi can't do without ads) and the fact that they didn't come close makes me think that they are holding something significant for next year.

Too bad. If my phone could wait for another year, I would wait for the next Google phone. But I guess the Samsung FE will be my pick for the next years.

Hmmm... I think given the phone's heavy reliance on post-processing via software, that Snapdragon 765G processor is going to be a bottleneck a year or two down the road. I bought the 128GB Pixel 2 XL shortly after it became available. Despite having the Snapdragon 835, it aged very poorly. I wasn't a heavy 3rd-party app user, and it became painfully slow even just launching native apps like the Google Camera app, and the photo processing time just kept on getting longer and longer that it became frustrating to use it for its camera prowess, which was the reason I got the phone.

I ended up getting the iPhone 11 last year shortly after it came out (partly due to the companies' respective stance on user data), and having had it for just more than a year, I wish I can say the Pixel 2 XL was still as snappy after a year's worth of regular use as the iPhone 11 is. The iPhone 11's battery also still keeps 97% of its original capacity, which isn't the same I can say about the Pixel 2 XL after the one-year mark.

I don't think Google should have skimped on getting better hardware. It's OK to not have top-tier specs or cutting edge features, but to regress on such a key component of the device without improving on the camera sensor front, add in the fact that Android devices tend to age poorly in general, would make it a no-buy for me if I was in the market for another Android device today.
